<h2 id="lessons" class="font-semibold text-xl mb-2 mt-4">Key Takeaways</h2>
<ol class="list-decimal list-inside mt-2">
  <li><a href="#learned1" class="text-yellow-700 dark:text-yellow-200">Balance your time!</a> Playtesting vs. Development.</li>
  <li><a href="#learned2" class="text-yellow-700 dark:text-yellow-200">Cater playtesting questions</a> to produce the most useful feedback.</li>
</ol>

<h2 id="plan" class="font-semibold text-xl mb-2 mt-4">Playtesting Plan</h2>
<p class="mb-2">Playtesting was at the core of our production timeline. In fact, our weekly schedule was centered around preparing for, executing, and reviewing playtests.</p>
<p>From the start of our project, we made playtesting a priority for these following reasons:</p>
<ol class="list-decimal ml-8">
  <li>Designing a platformer demands a considerabl amount of design and iteration work to create fun, unique and satisfying mechanics and levels.</li>
  <li>The leaf dash as a core abilitiy is unique to platformers and therefore needed additional iteration and refinement to ensure it benefitted the overall play experience.</li>
  <li>With the 8-week production period, we could not resonably rely on us naturally finding design trends and discovering wat was fun. We needed a way to guarantee we were reapidly assessing the game and making progress to "find the fun".</li>
</ol>

<h3 id="inspiration" class="font-semibold mt-4">Inspiration</h3>
<p class="mb-2">Our playtesting schedule & format drew heavily from the principles of “iterative game design”, outlined in Colleen Macklin and John Sharp’s book
  <a class="text-yellow-700 dark:text-yellow-200 italic" href="http://www.gamesdesignandplay.com/">Games, Design and Play</a>,
  as well as Valve’s playtesting philosophy outlined in Mark Brown’s article
  <a class="text-yellow-700 dark:text-yellow-200 italic" href="https://gmtk.substack.com/p/valves-secret-weapon">Valve's "Secret Weapon"</a>.
  We took these ideas to their extreme by playtesting every week and outlining specific goals for what we wanted to test for each playtest.
<p class="mb-2">

<h3 id="schedule" class="font-semibold mt-4">Schedule</h3>
<p>Our weekly schedule generally was as follows:</p>
<ul class="list-disc ml-8">
  <li><span class="italic">Monday through Wednesday</span>: prepare a prototype by adding and tweaking features</li>
  <li><span class="italic">Thursday</span>:
    <ul class="list-disc ml-8">
      <li>playtest with participants from our playtesting interest form</li>
      <li>take notes on player behaviours & discussions</li>
      <li>compile notes into quantitiative counts of behavior patterns and write summaries of key takeaways</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li><span class="italic">Fridays</span>: present data to the team and suggest possible changes and additionas to the game in response to the feedback</li>
</ul>

<h2 id="procon" class="font-semibold text-xl mb-2 mt-4">Pros and Cons</h2>
<p>Our playtesting plan successfully helped to guide our game design, but came at the cost of taking away development time and pressuring the team to rush changes out for playtesting builds.</p>

<h3 id="turnaround" class="font-semibold mt-4">One Week Turnaround</h3>
<p>Playtesting every week forced us to have one-week turnarounds. While there were some benefits to this, there were also quite a few downsides.</p>
<table class="mt-4 mb-6 border border-collapse table-fixed border-yellow-400 dark:border-yellow-800">
  <thead class="text-left text-lg bg-yellow-100 dark:bg-yellow-900/20">
    <tr>
      <th class="border pl-2 border-yellow-400 dark:border-yellow-800">Pros</th>
      <th class="border pl-2 border-yellow-400 dark:border-yellow-800">Cons</th>
    </tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr>
      <td class="border pl-2 border-yellow-400 dark:border-yellow-800">Ensured we had a playable build every week</td>
      <td class="border pl-2 border-yellow-400 dark:border-yellow-800">Caused rushed additions that then led to increased technical debt</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="border pl-2 border-yellow-400 dark:border-yellow-800">Allowed easy course-correction through close to immediate feedback on changes and additions</td>
      <td class="border pl-2 border-yellow-400 dark:border-yellow-800">Forced team to pick between fixing found issues or adding new features</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="border pl-2 border-yellow-400 dark:border-yellow-800"></td>
      <td class="border pl-2 border-yellow-400 dark:border-yellow-800">Left little time to curate questions for the next weeks playtesting based on the previous weeks results</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="border pl-2 border-yellow-400 dark:border-yellow-800"></td>
      <td class="border pl-2 border-yellow-400 dark:border-yellow-800">Was more stressful on the team</td>
    </tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<h3 id="collection" class="font-semibold mt-4">Data Collection</h3>
<p>We collected data through uninterrupted, hands-off observation of playtesters and a discussion period afterwards where we followed up on any interesting behaviors and asked about their impressions on broad game areas and specific areas we wanted feedback on. We found this method to be quite sucessful overall for our project.</p>
<table class="mt-4 mb-6 border border-collapse table-fixed border-yellow-400 dark:border-yellow-800">
  <thead class="text-left text-lg bg-yellow-100 dark:bg-yellow-900/20">
    <th class="border pl-2 border-yellow-400 dark:border-yellow-800">Pros</th>
    <th class="border pl-2 border-yellow-400 dark:border-yellow-800">Con</th>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr>
      <td class="border pl-2 border-yellow-400 dark:border-yellow-800">Helped us observe genuine player behavior</td>
      <td class="border pl-2 border-yellow-400 dark:border-yellow-800">Took time away from development</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="border pl-2 border-yellow-400 dark:border-yellow-800">Showed us where design pain points were</td>
      <td class="border pl-2 border-yellow-400 dark:border-yellow-800">Required longer prep-time to ensure that good data was recieved</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="border pl-2 border-yellow-400 dark:border-yellow-800">Allowed us to supplement our notes with direct qualitative feedback and suggestions from playtesters</td>
      <td class="border pl-2 border-yellow-400 dark:border-yellow-800">Does not work as well with playtesters who are less talkative</td>
    </tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<h3 id="compiling" class="font-semibold mt-4">Compiling Raw Data</h3>
<p>We compiled our playtesting data by transcribing our qualitative notes into quantitative numbers and then producing general summaries of the key takeaways. In restrospect, there were quite a few cons to this.</p>
<table class="mt-4 mb-6 border border-collapse table-fixed border-yellow-400 dark:border-yellow-800">
  <thead class="text-left text-lg bg-yellow-100 dark:bg-yellow-900/20">
    <th class="border pl-2 border-yellow-400 dark:border-yellow-800">Pros</th>
    <th class="border pl-2 border-yellow-400 dark:border-yellow-800">Cons</th>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr>
      <td class="border pl-2 pr-2 border-yellow-400 dark:border-yellow-800">Produces both qualitative and quantitative data</td>
      <td class="border pl-2 pr-2 border-yellow-400 dark:border-yellow-800">Detached data from important context from the session</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="border pl-2 border-yellow-400 dark:border-yellow-800"></td>
      <td class="border pl-2 border-yellow-400 dark:border-yellow-800">Numbers often ended up having little meaning</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="border pl-2 border-yellow-400 dark:border-yellow-800"></td>
      <td class="border pl-2 pr-2 border-yellow-400 dark:border-yellow-800">Time-consuming</td>
    </tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

{# LESSON 1 #}
<div class="mb-8 mt-8 rounded-lg p-2 border border-yellow-200 dark:border-yellow-800 bg-yellow-100 dark:bg-yellow-900/20 rounded-lg">
<h3 id="learned1" class="font-semibold">Lesson 1: Balance Playtesting Time</h3>
  <p class="ml-8">We underestimated the impact that 2 hours of playtesting meant in the time span of the one term MQP. This meant that playtesting cut into a more significant portion of development time than expected.</p>
</div>

